deck: Egyptian cartoonist and creator of controversial caricatures about religion and female genital mutilation.
name: Doaa Eladl

deck: Japanese sculptor and manga artist known for her work featuring female genitalia that has often got her into legal trouble and resulted in short-term arrests; being charged with "obscenity display". She uses the pseudonym "Rokudenashiko" (good-for-nothing girl, or bad girl).
name: Megumi Igarashi

deck: Formerly imprisoned Iranian cartoonist, political activist, and voice for women's rights.
name: Atena Farghadani

deck: The 24 Nengumi (or Year 24 Group or Forty-Niners) is one of the first female mangaka groups. They were all born in or before the year of Showa-24 (1949) and are known for their works often including sexuality and gender issues.
name: 24 Nengumi

deck: One of the first female manga artists. She started her first comic strip about a fictional Japanese housewife, Sazae-san, in 1946.
name: Machiko Hasegawa

deck: Silver Age cartoonist mostly known for creating the comic strip Teena.
name: Hilda Terry

deck: Golden Age cartoonist. Shermund (1899-1978) is one of the first female cartoonist at The New Yorker.
name: Barbara Shermund

deck: Golden Age illustrator and cartoonist known for creating the comic characters "Kewpies".
name: Rose O'Neill

deck: Golden Age cartoonist and illustrator of children's books known for the Campbell Soup Kids, Dolly Dimples, Dolly Dingle Paper Dolls, and The Pussycat Princess.
name: Grace Drayton

deck: Golden Age cartoonist and creator of the comic strip "Little Lulu".
name: Majorie Henderson Buell

deck: Golden Age illustrator, often credited as the "Queen of Comics", and creator of original comic strips like "The Fortunes of Flossie", "Romances of Gloriette", and "The Adventures of Prudence Prim".
name: Nell Brinkley

deck: Long-time Executive Director of the Comic Book Legal Defense Fund (CBLDF)
name: Charles Brownstein
